# AP-001 — What is a Bitcoin Digital Object?

**Status:** Draft v1.0

---

# Abstract

A **Bitcoin Digital Object (BDO)** is a digital object whose ownership is secured by Bitcoin.

Unlike traditional digital objects, a BDO is not defined by the application that created it, the platform that stores it or the service that manages it.

A Bitcoin Digital Object exists independently from any single application.

Ownership belongs to the user.

Verification belongs to everyone.

Applications simply provide experiences around the object.

This document defines the conceptual meaning of a Bitcoin Digital Object.

It intentionally remains independent from any specific implementation or interoperability specification.

---

# Introduction

Digital objects have existed since the early days of the Internet.

Documents.

Images.

Tickets.

Game items.

Memberships.

Certificates.

Collectibles.

These objects can usually be copied, controlled or revoked by the platform that created them.

Bitcoin introduced a different model.

For the first time, digital ownership could exist independently from the applications that expose it.

Bitcoin Digital Objects extend this principle beyond money.

They apply Bitcoin's ownership model to any digital object.

---

# Definition

A Bitcoin Digital Object (BDO) is a digital object whose ownership is secured by Bitcoin.

A BDO can be independently:

- owned
- transferred
- verified
- interpreted

across compatible applications.

Its existence does not depend on any individual company, marketplace or platform.

---

# The Object

A Bitcoin Digital Object is not merely data.

It represents a persistent digital object.

That object may correspond to many different real-world concepts.

Examples include:

- memberships
- tickets
- certificates
- collectibles
- identities
- licenses
- credentials
- access rights
- achievements
- game objects

The category intentionally remains broad.

A BDO describes **how ownership works**, not **what the object represents**.

---

# The User

The owner of a Bitcoin Digital Object controls the object.

Applications may assist the owner.

Applications do not own the object.

Changing applications never changes ownership.

Changing ownership never changes the object.

---

# The Application

Applications create experiences around Bitcoin Digital Objects.

Different applications may:

- display the object differently
- attach different metadata
- expose different capabilities
- provide different user experiences

Yet they all refer to the same underlying object.

Applications compete through experiences.

Not through ownership.

---

# The Platform

Platforms may issue Bitcoin Digital Objects.

Platforms may exchange them.

Platforms may verify them.

Platforms may disappear.

The Bitcoin Digital Object remains.

---

# Independence

A Bitcoin Digital Object is independent from:

- any application
- any marketplace
- any issuer
- any company
- any wallet

Its ownership is ultimately secured by Bitcoin.

---

# Open Category

Bitcoin Digital Objects are an open category.

No organization owns the concept.

No company controls the ecosystem.

No implementation defines the category.

Open interoperability specifications enable compatible implementations.

Reference implementations demonstrate what is possible.

The category itself remains open.

---

# Relationship with Specifications

This document intentionally does not define technical implementation details.

Serialization.

Transport.

Verification mechanisms.

Interoperability.

Those responsibilities belong to open specifications such as STAS-01.

This document defines only the conceptual meaning of a Bitcoin Digital Object.

---

# Design Goals

Bitcoin Digital Objects are designed to enable:

- digital ownership
- independent verification
- portability
- interoperability
- long-term continuity
- implementation independence

These properties allow digital objects to outlive individual applications and organizations.

---

# Guiding Principle

> A Bitcoin Digital Object is not defined by who created it.
>
> It is defined by who owns it.